---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro'
import Disclaimer from '../../../components/Disclaimer.astro'
import VerifyBadge from '../../../components/VerifyBadge.astro'
---

<Base
  title="The Bermuda Car Trap: Assessment Numbers Explained"
  description="Bermuda allows only one car per household via an Assessment Number system. Moving into an existing household? You can't bring your own car. Full explainer."
>
  <section class="hero" style="padding-block: var(--space-16);">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/move" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Moving</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Assessment Numbers</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">The Bermuda Car Trap</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        One car per household. Assessment Numbers explained — and why this surprises almost every mover.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- REQUIRED disclaimer -->
      <Disclaimer variant="relocation" />

      <h2>What is an Assessment Number?</h2>
      <p>
        An <strong>Assessment Number</strong> is a government-issued quota that allows a household to
        register one private car in Bermuda. Every household with car access needs one.
        The system exists to enforce Bermuda's strict <strong>one-car-per-household policy</strong>,
        which has been in place for decades as part of the island's traffic management strategy.
      </p>
      <p>
        The rule is simple but has a consequence that catches nearly every mover off-guard:
      </p>

      <div
        style="background-color: #fee2e2; border: 2px solid #dc2626; border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-6); margin-block: var(--space-8); text-align: center;"
        role="alert"
      >
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-xl); font-weight: 700; color: #991b1b; margin-bottom: var(--space-2); font-family: var(--font-serif);">
          If the household you're moving into already has a car, you cannot import another one.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #7f1d1d; font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0;">
          One Assessment Number = one car. Period.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        This means: if you're moving in with a partner, spouse, or family member who already has a car
        registered in Bermuda, <strong>your car stays behind.</strong> The Assessment Number for that
        household is already allocated.
      </p>

      <!-- Car import duty -->
      <h2>Car import duty</h2>
      <p>
        Even if you do have an Assessment Number available, importing a car from overseas is expensive:
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Assessed value band</th>
              <th>Duty rate</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>First $10,000 of assessed value</td>
              <td>75%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Above $10,000</td>
              <td>150%</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
        Plus freight, shipping insurance, Bermuda Customs clearance fees, and annual licence fees.
        <span class="unverified">[duty rates — verify at Bermuda Customs and Excise, <a href="https://www.gov.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">gov.bm</a>]</span>
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-10" />
      </p>
      <p>
        For most movers, it's more economical to sell your car before moving and buy locally —
        though the local used car market reflects the import duty cost in its pricing.
      </p>

      <!-- Interactive tool -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-8);">Does this apply to me?</h2>
      <p>Answer one question to understand your situation:</p>

      <!-- CSS-only state machine using radio inputs -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-6); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
        <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          Are you moving into an existing household where someone already has a car registered in Bermuda?
        </p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-3);">
          <label
            for="car-yes"
            style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); cursor: pointer; padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); background-color: var(--color-white);"
          >
            <input type="radio" id="car-yes" name="car-situation" value="yes" />
            <span><strong>Yes</strong> — I'm joining an existing household (partner, family, existing residents)</span>
          </label>

          <label
            for="car-no"
            style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); cursor: pointer; padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); background-color: var(--color-white);"
          >
            <input type="radio" id="car-no" name="car-situation" value="no" />
            <span><strong>No</strong> — I'm setting up a new household (fresh tenancy, no existing residents)</span>
          </label>
        </div>

        <!-- Conditional results using :has() or just always show both -->
        <div id="result-yes" style="display: none; margin-top: var(--space-5);" class="car-result">
          <div class="alert alert-warning">
            <strong>You are affected by the one-car rule.</strong>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: 0;">
              The household's Assessment Number is already allocated to the existing car.
              You will not be able to import your own car. Your options are:
            </p>
            <ul style="margin-top: var(--space-2); padding-left: var(--space-5);">
              <li>Share the household car</li>
              <li>Use scooters, minicars, and public transport as your second vehicle</li>
              <li>If the existing car is sold or de-registered, the Assessment Number becomes available again</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: 0; font-size: var(--text-sm);">
              Verify current rules at the <a href="https://www.gov.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Bermuda Department of Transport</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div id="result-no" style="display: none; margin-top: var(--space-5);" class="car-result">
          <div class="alert alert-info">
            <strong>You may be able to apply for an Assessment Number.</strong>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: 0;">
              As the sole/first resident of a new household, you can apply to the
              Bermuda Department of Transport for an Assessment Number.
              This allows you to register one car in Bermuda.
              Factor in the import duty costs if bringing a car from abroad.
            </p>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); margin-bottom: 0; font-size: var(--text-sm);">
              Verify the current application process and requirements at the
              <a href="https://www.gov.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Bermuda Department of Transport</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div style="margin-top: var(--space-8); padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6); background-color: var(--color-ocean-muted); border-radius: var(--radius-md);">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
          <strong>This is a simplified explainer.</strong>
          The Assessment Number rules have nuances around household composition, corporate vehicles,
          and scooter/minicar registration. Rules may have changed since this page was last updated.
          Verify at the
          <a href="https://www.gov.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Bermuda Department of Transport</a>
          before making any decisions.
          <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-10" />
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>

<script>
  // Simple radio-driven reveal — no framework needed
  const radios = document.querySelectorAll('input[name="car-situation"]')
  radios.forEach((radio) => {
    radio.addEventListener('change', (e) => {
      const value = (e.target as HTMLInputElement).value
      const resultYes = document.getElementById('result-yes')
      const resultNo = document.getElementById('result-no')
      if (resultYes) resultYes.style.display = value === 'yes' ? 'block' : 'none'
      if (resultNo) resultNo.style.display = value === 'no' ? 'block' : 'none'
    })
  })
</script>
